The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, delivered remarks at Joint Base Elmendorf-Richardson in Alaska, praising the missile defense system and the personnel involved in protecting the country from potential missile attacks. He discussed the progress made by the Trump administration in securing additional funding for missile defense and the provision of more ballistic missile interceptors. Pence also addressed his upcoming trip to Japan and South Korea, where he plans to strengthen alliances and reiterate the commitment to isolate North Korea economically and diplomatically until it abandons its nuclear and ballistic missile ambitions. He expressed the need to tell the truth about the North Korean regime and its oppressive nature, while also highlighting the possibility of a better future if the regime chooses to abandon its weapons programs. Pence mentioned that Alaska plays a significant role in missile defense and emphasized the readiness of the state and the country in responding to any threats. In response to a question about the recent stock market drop, Pence stated that market fluctuations are normal and the fundamentals of the U.S. economy remain strong. He highlighted positive indicators such as job growth and rising wages.